{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782939012,"nonce":"2Uk2GDXMtjpn6Q3cJLwFYdCx1Jc=","title":"The derive macros (`Table`, `ColumnType`, `Schema`, `View`, `CTE`, `Database`) currently ignore `///` doc comments on the structs and fields they process. Rust surfaces doc comments as `#[doc = \"...\"]` attributes, so the macro input already carries them — they're just dropped. Two things should flow from them:","message":"The schema model already reserves the space for this and the derives always leave it `None`:\n\n- `crates/squealy/src/model.rs` — `TableModel`, `ColumnModel`, and the view model each have a `comment: Option\u003cString\u003e` field (see the `pub struct ColumnModel` around line 54 and the `comment: None` literals the derives emit, e.g. around lines 979 / 1109 / 1125).\n\nA field's `///` doc comment should populate `ColumnModel.comment`, a table struct's `///` should populate `TableModel.comment`, etc. Backends can then render `COMMENT ON TABLE/COLUMN ...` (Postgres/MySQL) as part of `render_create`, and introspection can round-trip it — directly serving the DACFx-style full-fidelity schema-management goal.\n\n\nEach `Table` derive generates column marker types (`User::id` -\u003e `UserId`), projection fields, and a write builder. Re-emitting the source `#[doc]` attributes onto the generated public items would make a field's documentation show up on hover for the generated column markers and builder setters, not just the original struct field.\n\n\n- Collect docs by scanning `field.attrs` / `input.attrs` for `Meta::NameValue` with path `doc`, joining the string literals with newlines (the standard `///` -\u003e `#[doc]` desugaring; also accept explicit `#[doc = \"...\"]`). A small shared helper in `crates/squealy-macros/src/common.rs` keeps it uniform across the derives.\n- Part 1 (model `comment` population + DDL rendering + introspection round-trip) is the higher-value half and can land first; part 2 (doc propagation onto generated items) is a smaller ergonomic follow-up.\n- Multi-line and multiple `///` lines should concatenate in order. Escaping is already handled since we pass through string literals.\n\nRelates to the DDL-management design (the `squealy-model` crate as the schema source of truth) and to introspection fidelity (see the \"DDL model rejects introspectable shapes\" issue).","files":null}]}